T1  - Coupon and tax effects on new and seasoned bond yields and the measurement of the cost of debt capital
AU  - Shiller, Robert J.
AU  - Modigliani, Franco
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 7
IS  - 3
SP  - 297
EP  - 318
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/09/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(79)90017-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X79900175
AB  - A model of the tax structure of interest rates is developed and simple approximate expressions relating yield to coupon are derived. The effect on these simple expressions of alternative assumptions about holding period length, expectations of future interest rates, and other factors, is evaluated. It is shown that with recent U.S. yield averages the new-seasoned yield spread varies with the new-seasoned coupon spread as the theory prescribes. It is concluded that new issue yield averages should provide a more reliable measure of the cost of debt capital than is provided by seasoned yield averages.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - An intertemporal asset pricing model with stochastic consumption and investment opportunities
AU  - Breeden, Douglas T.
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 7
IS  - 3
SP  - 265
EP  - 296
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/09/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(79)90016-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X79900163
AB  - This paper derives a single-beta asset pricing model in a multi-good, continuous-time model with uncertain consumption-goods prices and uncertain investment opportunities. When no riskless asset exists, a zero-beta pricing model is derived. Asset betas are measured relative to changes in the aggregate real consumption rate, rather than relative to the market. In a single-good model, an individual's asset portfolio results in an optimal consumption rate that has the maximum possible correlation with changes in aggregate consumption. If the capital markets are unconstrained Pareto-optimal, then changes in all individuals' optimal consumption rates are shown to be perfectly correlated.
ER  - 

